Original version, with input summed to mono, dry on left output, and wet on right output.
Pitch Bend controls speed (up = fast, down = slow). Note that modulation modes are set to Direct Control; this works only with bipolar sources.
Original version, with input summed to mono, dry on left output, and wet on right output.
True stereo in-out
Mod Wheel toggles between fast and slow. Note that modulation modes are set to Toggle.
Pitch Bend controls speed (up = fast, down = slow). Note that modulation modes are set to Direct Control; this works only with bipolar sources.
True stereo input-output. (Original was mono-in, stereo-out.)
Original version, with input summed to mono, dry on left output, and wet on right output.
True stereo in-out
Original version, with input summed to mono, dry on left output, and wet on right output.
Kirnberger III. A "well-tempered" tuning from the Baroque period.
Octave-repeating Vina tuning

Just Intonation optimized for minor keys. This uses the "Octave Scale, A = Master Tune" type, so it maintains the A4 tuning (e.g. A=440 Hz) as set by the Master Tune parameter. To compensate, the root note of the selected Key may shift from its equal-tempered pitch.
Duplicate this to start an octave scale from scratch.
Major 3rd and major 7th provide quarter-tone intervals.
"Temperament ordinaire," aka "well-tempered" modified meantone tuning, circa 1690.
Perfect fifth divided into nine equal steps. 128-note scale; C is at "normal" pitch.
Bayati maqam (aka Husayni).
Bach tuning with seven pure fifths and five "well-tempered" fifths each reduced by 1/5 Pythagorean comma.
Standard Western tuning with equally-spaced semitones.
Duplicate this to start a 128-note scale from scratch.
This Indonesian gamelan scale uses seven notes per octave. When Key is set to C, use the white keys. The black keys will play the equal tempered pitches.
aka Tartini-Vallotti. 18th-century circulating temperament with five pure 5ths, six 5ths tempered by 1/6 syntonic comma, and a final 5th tempered by a schisma.
This Indonesian gamelan scale has five notes per octave. When Key is set to C, use C, D, F, G and A. Other notes will play the normal equal-tempered pitches.
In this 128-note tuning for acoustic pianos, notes below the middle of the keyboard are progressively more flat, and notes above the middle are progressively more sharp.
Perfect fifth divided into eleven equal steps. 128-note scale; C is at "normal" pitch.

Especially effective for melodies, this produces 11 completely pure fifths, at the expense of other intervals - thirds in particular. To maintain the tuning of the octave, the final fifth from sharp four to sharp root is also quite flat.
Werkmeister III. A "well-tempered" tuning from the Baroque period.
Rast on white keys; Wusta-Zalzal Arijaom sequence

Just Intonation optimized for major keys. This uses the "Octave Scale, A = Master Tune" type, so it maintains the A4 tuning (e.g. A=440 Hz) as set by the Master Tune parameter. To compensate, the root note of the selected Key may shift from its equal-tempered pitch.

Initialized Performance set up to match the vintage 2600, including Trim Pot settings. Set up for input processing: VCA Initial Gain at max, Keyboard modulation of VCF at zero. Post-FX volume at +13.0, for unity gain with audio input (signal is normalized to +10 V, similar to VCOs).
Initialized Performance set up to match the vintage 2600, including Trim Pot settings. VCO 3 set up for duophonic operation.
Mod Wheel toggles between fast and slow. Note that modulation modes are set to Toggle.
Pitch Bend controls speed (up = fast, down = slow). Note that modulation modes are set to Direct Control; this works only with bipolar sources.
Mod Wheel toggles between fast and slow. Note that modulation modes are set to Toggle.
Original version, with input summed to mono, dry on left output, and wet on right output.
True stereo in-out
True stereo in-out
Mono in-out (dry signal is stereo)

A stringy, phasey lead sound best used for aggressive melodies. Several paths of modulation contribute to an unstable, natural analog chorusing between oscillators. MW darkens tone and increases vibrato.

A soft, lo-fi style brass that utilizes, subtle random S/H modulation to give a worn, vintage texture to the sound. The lag processor softens the intensity of the S/H. All the places being affected by the S/H use a blue patch cable. Velocity allows you to play this patch dynamically, while being able to add vibrato on the MW. Increased drift range in the trim pot section adds more instability. DAP: Set trim pots to defaults (voice variation = nice for polyphony)
A punchy, overdriven, sub-focused bass utilizing hard sync. Mod wheel increases your, "squelch," raising the hard sync effect (osc 2 freq) and resonance.

A growly, rhythmic bass. This patch utilizes oscillator FM to achieve distortion. The lag processor takes the clock and, "breaks" it into an interesting driving rhythm, routed to the left and right output. This gives the bass a stereo dancing effect, perfect for any tense action sequence. MW introduces LFO to pitch and filter.

Meditative, drone-like 5th utilizing two separate filter motions; one initial fast swipe, and one slower more gradual opening and closing. This can also be used to play subtle, underscore melodies in the ambient genre. Mod wheel adds vibrato.
Mod Wheel changes between Saw and Square.

Great sequence for a, "contemplative" or introspective underscore. This utilizes the switch to pan the mix L/R at a rate half of the sequencer. This sequence is triggered by the key and will transpose as you change note. Mod wheel darkens the tone.

An "Edge-y" processor, using high gain on the Preamplifier for distortion, then passing through a resonant 4012 filter, followed by more distortion from the Drive circuit - and just a touch of signature dotted-note delay.
High gain version.

High gain version without ring mod. Audio input routed through envelope follower, modulating VCO 2 frequency, VCF and Mode-Sweep Filter frequencies, and VCF resonance and triggering the ADSR. Requires input with high transients, such as drums, clav, etc.
Audio input routed through ring modulator. Requires input with high transients, such as drums, clav, etc. Adjust Gain and Env Follower to the input signal.
Audio input through the Mode-Sweep Filter, with cutoff modulation from Aux LFO and Mode modulation from Vibrato LFO.
Pitchbend changes distortion. Mod Wheel changes speed of motion.

Play pretty in C! This duophonic patch allows you to play two layer melodies while oscillator 1 drones on a low C. Raising the mod wheel will drop that pitch to F for some nice 1-4-1 action. Oscillator 1 is processed through both the main VCF and Mode-Sweep Filter to increase the complexity of the drone. VCO2 has glide the other oscillators do not thanks to the lag processor.
MW controls S/H clock rate
Envelope Follower, through Lag processor, controls VCF Frequency. Adjust Gain, Env Follower, and Lag amount for desired response.

Audio input goes through Ring Mod, then VCA, then VCF. Dry audio input is routed to a second VCF input.  Envelope Follower, through Lag filter, controls VCA level for Ring Mod. Vibrato LFO modulates pitch of VCO2, for RIng Mod.
Envelope Follower, through Lag processor, controls VCF Frequency. Adjust Gain, Env Follower and Lag amount for desired response.

Envelope Follower, through Lag processor, controls VCF Frequency, Mode-Sweep Filter Frequency, and VCA level.. Noise goes through Mode-Sweep Filter, adding emphasis to signal peaks. Adjust Gain, Env Follower, and Lag amount for desired response.
Envelope Follower, through Lag processor, controls VCF Frequency. Adjust Cutoff, Env Follower, and Lag amount for desired response.
Has Sync Issues when MW is turned up
MW = Phaser
Mod Wheel controls VCO 2 FM and VCA Frequency. Aftertouch brings in square wave LFO.
Over-driven, growlu bass using two lanes of drive, ring mod, high moving resonance and subtle filter motion from the sequencer. MW increases overdrive if you really want to grumble!
Velocity and Mod Wheel control of decay/timbre
Velocity and Mod Wheel control of decay/timbre
Velocity and Mod Wheel control of decay/timbre

Mod Wheel changes chord from minor, major, and sus4. 
Pitchbend changes Wha effect.
Spooky, motion-based ambient a-tonal texture perfect for any horror or suspense underscore! MW increases the amount of warble and brightens the tone.
Mod Wheel controls tuning.
Mod Wheel increases Preamp Gain for overdrive & brightness. Wait a second after selection for resonance to build up. Keyboard controls pitch; C4 is a good start.
Mod Wheel controls tuning.
Audio input through the Mode-Sweep Filter set to BP (Bandpass), with cutoff modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through the Mode-Sweep Filtet set to Highpass, with modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through the Mode-Sweep Filtet set to Lowpass, with modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through VCF set to LP1, with modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through VCF set to LP2 (the ARP 4072 filter module), with modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through VCF set to BP (Bandpass), with modulation from Aux LFO.
Audio input through VCF set to HP (Highpass), with modulation from Aux LFO.

Classic analog synth string patch utilizing PWM and a key-tracked vibrato. The lag processor smooths out Osc 3 pulse as a mod source. Increased velocity opens filter and slows attack. MW raises volume of Osc 2. DAP: set trim pots to defaults (voice variation = nice for polyphony)
Hold low octaves

Self-playing sequence that utilizes one sequencer using an odd grouping of notes against the other. This allows for a longer play length without feeling monotonous. MW brightens tone and increases driven ring mod in the VCA. Sequence will transpose on key press. DAP: patched GATE to AR GATE IN, so that the keyboard still gates the note.

Self-playing sequence meant for a pensive, driving feel. MW reveals a high, subtle counter melody via ring mod and Osc 3. DAP: Gate to AR in; AR Time to Fast; AR Rel time to 50%; multiply AR and ADSR, patch result to VCA Control in place of ADSR

This sound can be used as an interesting bass or lead. It utilizes an inverted envelope on filter, ring mod controlling oscillator volume and the aux envelope giving a harsh release trigger. MW controlls vibrato.
Play low octaves
Mod Wheel controls ADSR sustain, for brightness; vibrato on aftertouch.
High gain version.
Mod Wheel changes Mode-Sweep Filter cutoff and modulations. Main VCF highpass filters out low-frequency thumps.
Play a chord and let the arp do it's thing! MW increases release time, brightens tone and increases volume of Osc 1. Osc 1 features square wave LFO modulation giving it an octave, "flicker" effect.

Make our friend from a galaxy far, far away speak! This patch works best with single key presses of various lengths, raising the MW to increase "frantic-ness" of speech. DAP: increased ADSR release time slightly to avoid clicks at note-off.

A fun brass pad that utilizes a slow ramp LFO to increase the speed of Osc 2, modulating the cutoff of the filter. This gives a fast, "spiraling up" effect that resets rapidly. Catching the ramp at various points in its cycle can create interesting various effects. Velocity increases ADSR intensity and MW adds vibrato. Try rolling your chords on this one.
Cogumelo de Ravel

Very resonant, thick bass sound which utilizes a looped Aux envelope creating complex PWM and a lagged trig creating a short blip in the pitch of Osc 2. MW increases vibrato. DAP: changed Trigger MULT to SINGLE for legato ability.
Audio input routed through ring modulator. Requires input with high transients, such as drums, clav, etc.

A very snappy polyphonic ARP that wires the trig into the S&H section, functionally creating a different random value on each note. This is routed to the pitch of all oscillators at various subtle depths as well as the filter. Try turning the Arpeggiator off and playing rolled chords! MW controlls filter brightness and vibrato.
Arpeggiator + Two Sequencers! Single notes are fun, but also try playing 2 note intervals (2nds, 3rds, 7ths, etc.). Then  try 3 note chords, major, minor, 4ths. Less is more.  :)

An aggressive, modulated lead where two of the oscillatots, "split" away from the root on attack and return on release. This utilizes ring modulation and filter FM. MW adds vibrato, increases brightness, filter FM and ring modulation in the VCA, giving added growl and motion.

High gain audio input routed through envelope follower, modulating VCO 2 frequency, VCF and Mode-Sweep Filter frequencies, and VCF resonance and triggering the ADSR. 2-bar LFO also modulates filters. Best for signals with high transients, such as drums, clav etc.

Motion-focused pad utilizing two separate envelopes controlling the two different filters, routed to L/R, giving the effect of throwing the filter  envelope opening from left to right. MW increases vibrato as well as both filter FM's, giving even more fast motion to the stereo field. DAP: re-routed multiply to the Ring Modulator, avoiding the apparent bug in the Voltage Processors.
Noisy pluck that alternates L/R channel on each note. MW increases wave FM for a gnarly warping effect! DAP: set trim pots to defaults
Hold for sweep
A clean, 3 oscillator bass sound utilizing hard sync. MW increases the hard sync pitch ADSR effect and adds delayed vibrato.
A simple, vowel-like vocal swipe that could easily add some spice to either a bassline or lead! MW splits the pitch distance between oscillators 1 and 2, creating a more nasal and narrow formant.

A noisy lead meant to emulate chracteristics of a breathy wind instrument, similar to a saxophone. The aux envelope controling the volume of noise simulates a breath while several FM and ring mod routings contribute to the growl. MW opens the filter.

Similar to the lead used by Tony Banks on Genesis', "Wot Gorilla?" Tony was known for using ARPs throughout Genesis' history, including the 2600. This is one of my favorite leads of all time. While simple on the surface, nailing the intricacies of this sound makes it suitable to stand on its own or double any guitar line. MW raises drive/overall volume.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod Wheel controls vibrato.

From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Slowly raise mod wheel, then play quickl rhythms on pitch bend wheel. For the original effect, also lower Filter Control VCO 2 before playing pitch bend rhythms.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod wheel and AT raise VCO 2 filter mod for vibrato; exp vel modulates ADSR filter mod for brightness
Clarinet from the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod Wheel and AT control vibrato depth (VCO 2->VCO 1) and rate (VCO 2 Frequency).
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod wheel controls vibrato.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Uses VCO 3 Saw as input. Mod Wheel adjusts VCO 2 frequency.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Uses VCO 2 SAW as input, and PULSE output to create a stepped on/off signal for the keyboard split.

From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Uses KBD GATE as input. "ADSR release determines number of repeats, Echo is used on singe notes only - AR is repeating envelope on fade-out. AR can be altered for repeated "wow" effect (controlled by mod wheel). Adjust S/H Rate for repeat rate."
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Uses KBD TRIG as input. MW controls S/H clock.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Uses KBD GATE as input.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod Wheel reduces VCO 2 pitch modulation of VCOs 1 and 3.
From the original ARP 2600 Patch Book. Mod Wheel raises ADSR level into VCF Control.
